    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-02-27T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-02-27T02:00:00-05:00" n="533"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d533">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6593: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-02-27T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 27, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 27—9:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>130. My 95, February 8, 2 p.m.<note n="81" xml:id="d533fn81">Not printed.</note>
                    I learned from source near Soong<note n="82" xml:id="d533fn82">T. V. Soong,
                        chairman of the Board of Directors, Bank of China, and formerly Chinese
                        Minister of Finance.</note> that C. T. Wang is being recalled for apparently
                    misinforming Government about prospects for loan in the United States which
                        Kung<note n="83" xml:id="d533fn83">H. H. Kung, President of the Chinese
                        Executive Yuan (Premier) and Minister of Finance.</note> hoped to apply to
                    purchase of planes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
